  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Let u and v be permutations on n letters, with <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>u</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>v</mi></math> in Bruhat order. A Bruhat interval polytope <math altimg="si103.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="sans-serif">Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>v</mi></mrow></msub></math> is the convex hull of all permutation vectors <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> with <math altimg="si319.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>u</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>z</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>v</mi></math> . Note that when <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>e</mi></math> and <math altimg="si6.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math> are the shortest and longest elements of the symmetric group, <math altimg="si7.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="sans-serif">Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></msub></math> is the classical permutohedron. Bruhat interval polytopes were studied recently in [15] by Kodama and the second author, in the context of the Toda lattice and the moment map on the flag variety.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
  </datafield>
